Zimbabwe soybean trials

Cultivar recommendation is a critical stage in plant breeding programs, and selecting superior varieties for multiple traits remains a challenge due to the variety \(\times\) environment (V \(\times\) E) interaction. To understand better this chalenge we can analyse the Figure @ref(fig:gxe-selected), where is highlighted the Grain Yield overall mean soybean varietis performance across all locations and years. The Varieties show differencial performance across locations and years because of the variety x interaction effect, which leads to differencial gene expression interacting with soils, humidity, rainfall, temperature, elevation, photoperiod and others factors.

In this sense, the mean isnt the better way to selecting stable varieties, otherwise its possible to use statistical methods that accounts V x E interaction and selecting stable varieties. We show at Figure \(\ref{gxe-selected}\) the top 5 soybean varieties selected using the Bayesian Probabilistic selection index in contrast to the varieties in position 17 (S1150/5/22) and 36 (S1079/6/7) on overall BPSI rank (B) and (C) the best variety (Opal).

The BPSI selected ten soybean varieties (V003,V004,V013, V016, V020, V021, V032, V038, V045, V050) which have the greater distance to the worst variety performance per trait. Furthermore, the selected varieties have achieved probabilities above 60% for grain yield, 80% for plant height, and 50% for plant lodging, indicating greater yield stability and reduced selection risk.
